ection VI-D.\nas soon as the ground truth is published, and to reporting the               d) Granularity and validity of ten-clip calibration: With\noutcome in this section whatever it is.                                nt =10 the quantile map has data support only down to\n                                                                       exceedance 1/11 ≈ 0.091; nearly all of the pAUC range is\n                                                                       extrapolated, and pAUC additionally pools domains, so the\nG. Computational cost (E6)                                             support boundary maps onto the metric only loosely. Empiri-\n  All results were produced on one consumer GPU (RTX                   cally the maps undercover under train→test session shift: the\n4070 Ti SUPER, 16 GB). Embedding extraction dominates and              realized false-positive rate exceeds the nominal level (≈0.21\nruns once (table V); on cached embeddings a full per-machine           at nominal 0.10, section VI-B), i.e., the calibrated threshold is\nconfiguration cycle (base scores, LOO, calibration, and the            anti-conservative in absolute terms even where cross-domain\n10-split criterion) takes ∼0.15 s on CPU, so the complete 51-          balance improves. The weighted-conformal small-n analysis\nconfiguration × 15-machine study runs in under four minutes            of [21] and group-conditional constructions [18] suggest prin-\nper backbone. Peak extraction VRAM is below 1 GB.                      cipled refinements.\n                                                                             e) Criterion scale across families: The criterion’s abso-\n              VII. D ISCUSSION AND L IMITATIONS                        lute value is not perfectly comparable across method families\n                                                                       (hard-assignment configurations outperform soft ones by up to\n      a) Why does the criterion transfer while dev Ω does not?:        ≈2.3 Ω points at closely matched criterion values (|∆C| <\nThe criterion measures how well a configuration equalizes              0.005); within-family it is reliable. Cross-family selection\nthe two domains’ normal-score distributions—a property of              should therefore be read as region-selection, consistent with\nthe operating point, not of any machine’s anomaly geometry.            the 0.21-point oracle gap on the E3 grid (the gaps are 0.9 and\nThe evaluation machines reward balance (raw target AUCs                1.25 on EAT and PANNs, table II).\nas low as 33.7 on CoffeeGrinder; per-machine table in                        f) Threats to validity: (i) Post-challenge ground truth\nthe Appendix); several dev machines punish it (section VI-B).          could leak through experimenter iteration; selection signals are\nA signal tied to threshold placement rather than to dev-set            computed from training normals (plus dev labels for the veto),\nanomaly idiosyncrasies tracks the quantity that generalizes.           the pipeline was audited for leakage, and headline numbers\n      b) Scope of the transfer evidence: On dev machines the           were reproduced by the official evaluator on exported scores.\ncriterion does not predict dev Ω (ρs =+0.16); blind selection          (ii) The evaluation set is scored offline; the evaluator is the\nthere would have cost 2.7 points. Our claim is not that the            official one. (iii) Criterion seeds shift composed selection by\ncriterion predicts any set’s performance, but that it predicts         ±0.12 Ω; fixed-configuration picks can flip within the 59.3–\nevaluation performance where dev Ω does not—and the three-             59.6 cluster. (iv) The veto was introduced after observing\nyear replication (section VI-F) bounds this claim honestly.            a failure case and its meta-choices are disclosed, not pre-\nWhat replicates without exception across 2023/2024/2025 and            registered.\nacross three backbones: dev Ω is never a reliable selec-\ntion signal—it swings from useless to coincidentally optimal\n                                                                                            VIII. C ONCLUSION\n(PANNs; the 2023 dev pick gained +4.3 over raw) and\none cannot know in advance which regime applies—and a                    We reframed the two open problems of first-shot domain-\nwell-balanced degenerate configuration always exists in the            generalized ASD—the source/target trade-off and dev→eval\n\f                                                                   10\n\n\n\nnon-transfer—as calibration and model-selection problems.\nA per-domain quantile-calibration layer with a shrinkage\nknob makes calibration strength selectable; a label-free cross-\nvalidated balance criterion, paired with a coarse dev-side via-\nbility veto, selects the operating point. Across three challenge\nyears, development score is never a reliable selection signal\nand well-balanced degenerate configurations always lurk in the\npool; the criterion’s demonstrated transfer is concentrated in\nDCASE 2025, where it lifts a training-free frozen-embedding\nsystem from below the official baseline to fourth place among\nchallenge teams at ∼0.15 s per configuration cycle—while\nin both replication years a fixed full-equalization default\nmatches or beats criterion-based selection. The method applies\nunchanged on top of any frozen embedding and training-free\nbackend; the frozen DCASE 2026 forward test, fixed before\nthe per-clip evaluation ground truth became available, will\nextend the evidence prospectively.\n\n              DATA AND C ODE AVAILABILITY\n   The DCASE Task 2 datasets are public on Zenodo:\n2025 (records 15097779, 15392814, 15519362), 2023\n(7882613, 7830345, 7860847), 2024 (10902294, 11259435,\n11363076), and the 2026 development set (19336329);\n2023/2024 evaluation ground truth comes from the official\nnttcslab/dcase202{3,4}_task2_evaluator\nrepositories, and the pre-registration of the 2026\nforward test (frozen configuration, artifact hashes) is\nPREREGISTRATION.md in our repository. The 2025\nground truth is published in the official evaluator repository\n(nttcslab/dcase2025_task2_evaluator).\nAll    experiment      code,    per-machine       result  CSVs,\ndiagnostic    artifacts,    and     the     scripts    computing\nevery statistic in this paper (bootstrap CIs, FPR\ncoverage, criterion floor, differential metric test) are\navailable at https://github.com/polestvr/daco-experiments.\nBackbone checkpoints: BEATs iter3+ AS2M, EAT\nworstchan/EAT-base_epoch30_pretrain                        (both\nMIT), PANNs Cnn14_16k_mAP=0.438 (Zenodo record\n3987831,     CC-BY).        The      local-density-normalization\ncomparison is a clean-room reimplementation from\nthe published equations; the AGPL-licensed reference\nimplementation was not consulted.\n\n                          A PPENDIX\n                  P ER -M ACHINE R ESULTS\n  Table VI reports per-machine metrics (BEATs backbone) for\nthe dev-selected system (raw kNN), the E3 criterion pick (conf.\nsoft m=0, k=1), and the guarded pick (DAC O on LDN-ratio\nK=1).\n\f                                                                                                  11\n\n\n\n\n                                             TABLE VI\n           P ER - MACHINE RESULTS (BEAT S ; %). F OR EACH SYSTEM : AUCs / AUCt / pAUC.\n\n                    raw kNN (k=1)             conf. soft m=0, k=1         DAC O on LDN (K=1)\nMachine         AUCs    AUCt      pAUC      AUCs     AUCt      pAUC      AUCs     AUCt     pAUC\ndevelopment machines\nbearing         60.6     48.0      57.5      60.3     49.1      57.6      67.1     64.2    62.5\nfan             61.2     41.2      48.8      52.3     49.7      48.4      43.4     57.0    52.3\ngearbox         65.5     51.2      55.0      61.2     53.9      55.0      63.4     58.0    54.6\nslider   